    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-12-08T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-12-08T12:00:00-05:00" n="362"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d362">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">816.01/274: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Guatemala (<persName corresp="#p_WS1"
                            type="from">Whitehouse</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Guatemala</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-12-08T11:00:00-06:00"
                            >December 8, 1932—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 1:40 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>84. Minister of Foreign Affairs tells me that he had a meeting yesterday with
                        <persName corresp="#p_PL1">Pacheco</persName> and the Honduran and Mcaraguan
                    representatives, at which <persName corresp="#p_PL1">Pacheco</persName> asked
                    them to sign an agreement to recognize <persName corresp="#p_MH1"
                        >Martínez</persName>, intimating that such a move would not be regarded
                    unfavorably by the United States.</p>
                <p>The others refused, and <persName corresp="#p_SKA1">Skinner Klee</persName> again
                    brought forward his suggestion of a Committee of Inquiry. There was also some
                    talk about article 5.</p>
                <p>I pointed out to the Minister for Foreign Affairs the objections to his own
                    proposal and that an attempt to recognize <persName corresp="#p_MH1"
                        >Martínez</persName> now would make them appear foolish. I added that under
                    no circumstances would my Government recognize <persName corresp="#p_MH1"
                        >Martínez</persName>, which I understand to be the case.</p>
                <p>Repeated to all Central American missions.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_WS1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Whitehouse</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
